<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-03T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-03T15:00:00-05:00" n="374" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d374">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/401</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MCK1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Moser</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-03T16:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">June 3,
                                            1918, 4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>For <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName>:</p>
                            <p>Your May 25, 6 p.m. Do not be discouraged. You have accomplished more
                                than at short range you can perhaps realize. Railway improvement is
                                essential for all real help to Russia. No other American has your
                                intimate knowledge of Russian railways. Department will keep you
                                fully advised, but your services can not be spared now.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_LR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>